<paragraph blockId="7.[192,1440,397,486]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,323,397,421]" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Remarks.</emphasis>
The black elytra with a narrow, lateral, yellow border distinguish this species from all other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1850" box="[318,415,429,453]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Pentilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[318,415,429,453]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">Pentilia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon &amp; F &amp; Hanley" authorityYear="2019" box="[511,602,430,453]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Pentilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="traci">
<emphasis box="[511,602,430,453]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">P. traci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter species is Brazilian with a wider lateral border on each elytron and has different male genitalia; see description under 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon &amp; F &amp; Hanley" authorityYear="2019" box="[964,1053,462,485]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Pentilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="6" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="traci">
<emphasis box="[964,1053,462,485]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="6">P. traci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
